}}

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">Making labels and legends headings</h3>

<h4 class="govuk-heading-s">Labels as page headings with subheadings</h4>

<p class="govuk-body">If your headings are also the label of a form input, add the <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code> above the form component.</p>

{{
  example({
    item: 'page-heading',
    example: 'heading-as-label-with-subheading',
    welsh: 'heading-as-label-with-subheading-welsh',
    htmlOnly: 'true',
    description: 'Page heading as label with subheading'
  })
}}

<h4 class="govuk-heading-s">Legends as page headings with subheadings</h4>

<p class="govuk-body">If your headings are within a form legend, add the <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code> above the forms fieldset.</p>

{{
  example({
    item: 'page-heading',
    example: 'legends-as-page-headings-with-subheading',
    welsh: 'legends-as-page-headings-with-subheading-welsh',
    htmlOnly: 'true',
    description: 'Legend as page heading with subheading'
  })
}}

<p class="govuk-body">We use this method rather than the <a href="https://design-system.service.gov.uk/styles/typography/#headings-with-captions">gov.uk ‘caption’ component</a> as we believe it performs better for users of screen readers. This is because many screen reader users navigate the page using heading tags. This means:

<ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
  <li>captions before the <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> are often skipped</li>
  <li>captions nested within the <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> can be repetitive</li>
</ul>

<p class="govuk-body">Beginning the page with an <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code> tag, although unusual, avoids these issues.</p>


<h2 class="govuk-heading-l">Error messages</h2>

<p class="govuk-body">Error messages should be styled like this:</p>

